  2. Replace Image Placeholders:

    • Hero Image: Replace hero-image.jpg with your AI-generated hero image.

  3. AI Image Generation Prompts: Use the following creative prompts in your AI image generator to create custom visuals:

    • AC Service Cleaning Image: "A minimal and clean image of an AC unit being serviced, set against a modern, uncluttered background."

  4. Downloadable File: Once you’ve copied the code into a file named index.html, you can distribute or upload it to your web server. If you need a downloadable file, simply right-click on the file in your file explorer and select “Send to” or “Compress” it into a ZIP archive to share.

Below is a step-by-step guide on how to upload your website (HTML file and images folder) to GitHub and publish it using GitHub Pages.

Step 1: Create a GitHub Account (If You Haven’t Already)

  1. Visit and sign up for an account if you don't already have one.

  2. Confirm your email address and log in.

Step 2: Create a New Repository

  1. Once logged in, click the "+" icon at the top right and select "New repository".

  2. Name your repository:

    • If you want a personal website, name your repository as username.github.io (replace username with your GitHub username). This naming convention tells GitHub to deploy your site at https://username.github.io.

    • For a project website, you can give it any name (like my-website), and you'll later configure GitHub Pages to use it.

  3. Optionally add a description.

  4. You can choose to initialize the repository with a README (this is optional).

  5. Click "Create repository".

Step 3: Prepare Your Website Files Locally

  1. Ensure that your website files (i.e., your index.html and your images folder) are all in one folder on your computer.

  2. If your files are not already in a Git repository, you can initialize one.

    Using the Terminal/Command Prompt:

    bash
    cd path/to/your/website-folder
git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit - add website files"

Step 4: Link Your Local Repository to GitHub

  1. If you initialized your repository locally: In your terminal, link it to your GitHub repository by running:

    bash
    git remote add origin https://github.com/yourusername/your-repository-name.git
git branch -M main   # (if not already using "main")
git push -u origin main

  2. Alternatively, if you prefer using GitHub Desktop:

    • Download and install .

    • Open the application and clone your repository from GitHub.

    • Simply drag and drop your website files into the cloned repository folder, then commit and push through GitHub Desktop’s interface.

Step 5: Enable GitHub Pages

  1. Go to your repository on GitHub.

  2. Click on the "Settings" tab (usually located at the top of your repository page).

  3. Scroll down (or find the sidebar) until you see the "Pages" section.

  4. Under "Source", select the branch you want to use (typically the main branch) and the folder (commonly set as / (root) if your index.html is in the root of the repository).

  5. Click the "Save" button.

  6. After a few moments, GitHub will provide you with the URL where your site is published (e.g., https://yourusername.github.io/ for a personal site, or https://yourusername.github.io/your-repository-name/ for a project site).

Step 6: Verify Your Website

  1. Open your web browser and navigate to the GitHub Pages URL provided.

  2. Your website should now be live. If you make any changes to your files, be sure to commit and push those updates; GitHub Pages will automatically update your site.

Additional Tips

  • Folder Structure: Make sure your index.html is in the root directory of your repository, and that your images folder is correctly linked within your HTML. For example, if your images are in a folder named images, your HTML should reference them as <img src="images/your-image.jpg" alt="Description">.

  • Custom Domain (Optional): If you have your own custom domain, GitHub Pages allows you to configure a custom domain through the repository’s Pages settings.

  • Future Updates: Every time you update your website (change the HTML, update images, etc.), use:

    bash
    git add .
git commit -m "Describe your changes"
git push

    This way, your changes will automatically be deployed to GitHub Pages.

By following these steps, you'll have your website uploaded and live on GitHub Pages in no time. If you need more help or want to dive deeper into version control or customizations, feel free to ask!

u give me image generation prompts can u confime me whish size i can make by ai

Copilot said

When it comes to generating images for your website with an AI tool, the ideal dimensions usually depend on where you'll use each image. However, here’s a guideline you can follow:

  • Hero Image: For the main banner area at the top of your website, a Full HD resolution of 1920×1080 pixels is common. This gives you a wide, crisp background that scales well on various screens. If your design uses a specific aspect ratio (like 16:9), you can tailor the dimensions accordingly.

  • Service Images: For images illustrating your services (water filter installation, AC repair, etc.), you might want something around 1280×720 pixels. This size provides sufficient detail without being too heavy for web loading times. If your layout calls for square images, around 1080×1080 or 800×800 pixels can work nicely.

  • Thumbnails or Icons: For smaller areas such as icons or thumbnails, dimensions around 400×400 pixels are often a good choice. You can also adjust based on the specific design requirements of your site.

  • General Tips:

    • Consistency: Try to maintain a consistent aspect ratio across similar image categories (service images, icons, etc.) to preserve a uniform look.

    • Optimization: Make sure to optimize images for web use—ideally keeping file sizes small (usually under 500KB if possible) to ensure fast loading times. Tools like TinyPNG, JPEGmini, or built-in options in your AI generator (if available) can help compress images without significant loss of quality.

    • AI Generator Limitations: Some AI models (like Stable Diffusion or others) come with default sizes (often starting at 512×512 or 1024×1024). You might need to upscale using either the model’s built-in upscaling feature or an external tool to match the desired dimensions.

    • Responsive Design: Consider providing multiple image resolutions using HTML's srcset attribute if your website aims to support various devices and screen sizes.

By balancing quality and performance through careful selection and optimization of image sizes, you can ensure your website not only looks advanced and appealing but also loads efficiently.

When generating AI images with a 16:9 ratio, here are some common dimensions you might consider:

  • Hero Image (Main Banner): A popular choice is 1920×1080 pixels, a Full HD resolution that maintains a 16:9 aspect ratio. This size is ideal for large hero images and works well on most screens.

  • Service Images: For images in sections such as your services, 1280×720 pixels is a common 16:9 resolution. It offers a balance between detail and file size for fast web loading.

  • General Flexibility:

    • If you’re designing for mobile or smaller screens, you might generate smaller resolutions using the same 16:9 ratio (for example, 854×480 pixels or 640×360 pixels).

    • For thumbnails or preview images, you can downscale while keeping the ratio intact.

Below is a step-by-step guide to help you upload your website files (HTML and images folder) to GitHub and publish your site using GitHub Pages. Follow these steps carefully:

Step 1: Create or Log In to Your GitHub Account

  1. Go to and log in with your account. If you don't have an account yet, click Sign up and follow the instructions to create one.

Step 2: Create a New Repository

  1. Once logged in, click the "+" icon in the top-right corner (next to your profile picture) and select "New repository".

  2. Name Your Repository:

    • For a personal website, name the repository as username.github.io (replace username with your actual GitHub username).

    • For a project site, you can name it any way you like (e.g., mywebsite).

  3. Optionally, add a repository description.

  4. Choose whether the repository will be Public or Private (for GitHub Pages, Public is ideal).

  5. You may leave the option to Initialize this repository with a README unchecked if you plan to push your local files.

  6. Click "Create repository".

Step 3: Prepare Your Website Files Locally

  1. Create a folder (e.g., named MyWebsite) on your computer.

  2. Place your index.html file and the images folder (which contains all your photos, logo, etc.) in this folder. Your folder structure should look like this:

    MyWebsite/
├── index.html
└── images/
    ├── hero-image.jpg
    ├── ai-water-filter.jpg
    ├── ai-ac-installation.jpg
    ├── ai-ac-service.jpg
    └── logo.jpeg

Step 4: Upload Your Files to GitHub

There are two main methods to upload your files:

Method A: Using Git (via the Command Line)

  1. Open Terminal (or Command Prompt): Navigate to your MyWebsite folder:

    bash
    cd path/to/MyWebsite

  2. Initialize a Git Repository:

    bash
    git init

  3. Add All Files:

    bash
    git add .

  4. Commit the Files:

    bash
    git commit -m "Initial commit: add website files"

  5. Link Your Local Repository to GitHub: Replace yourusername and repository-name with your details (if you used the GitHub Pages naming convention for a personal site, use that):

    bash
    git remote add origin https://github.com/yourusername/your-repository-name.git

  6. Push Your Files to GitHub:

    bash
    git branch -M main
git push -u origin main

Method B: Using GitHub Web Interface

  1. In your GitHub repository page, click on "Add file" and then choose "Upload files".

  2. Drag and drop your index.html file and the entire images folder (you can drag the folder from your file explorer) into the upload area.

  3. Scroll down, add a commit message (e.g., "Initial commit: Add website files"), and then click "Commit changes".

Step 5: Enable GitHub Pages

  1. In your repository on GitHub, click on the "Settings" tab (usually on the right side of the repository navigation).

  2. Scroll down (or find in the sidebar) until you see the "Pages" section.

  3. Under the "Source" dropdown, select the branch you want to use (usually main) and set the folder as / (root) if your index.html is in the main directory.

  4. Click "Save".

  5. GitHub will display a message with the published site URL (for example, https://yourusername.github.io/ for a personal site or https://yourusername.github.io/repository-name/ for a project site). It might take a few minutes for the site to become live.

Step 6: Verify and Update Your Site

  1. Open your web browser and go to the GitHub Pages URL provided. You should see your website live with all the images and contact details.

  2. If you need to update any content, make changes locally or directly on GitHub, commit, and push the changes.

  3. GitHub Pages automatically updates your website based on the changes you push.

Extra Tips

  • Consistent File Paths: Ensure your index.html correctly points to your images. For example, images should be referenced like <img src="images/hero-image.jpg" alt="Hero Image">.

  • Custom Domain (Optional): If you have a custom domain, GitHub Pages allows you to configure it in the Pages settings.

  • Local Testing: Before uploading, open your index.html file from your local folder in a browser to ensure all links and images work correctly.

By following these steps, you'll have your website hosted on GitHub Pages, and it will be accessible to the world. If you have any questions or run into any problems along the way, feel free to ask!
